    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That's a great start. My students are going to have questions though, especially about the tension between this and the more traditional \"procedural\" view. Could you add a section or a few bullet points that explain why some legal scholars argue this expansion of rights is actually a problem for the legal system? I want them to see the debate.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Certainly, after discussing the protective role of substantive due process and highlighting its historical importance in expanding civil liberties, it's important to present a balanced perspective. Some legal scholars express concern about the potential for substantive due process to overstep its bounds:\n\n- Substantive due process can sometimes conflict with the concept of separation of powers by allowing the judiciary to usurp legislative authority, effectively creating new rights or limits without explicit constitutional text or legislative action.\n\n- Critics argue that by relying on the notion of \"fundamental rights,\" the judiciary can err in identifying which rights warrant the same level of protection, potentially disregarding social consensus or democratic principles.\n\n- This approach can introduce subjectivity and uncertainty into the law, as it suggests certain rights are inherently valuable and must be protected from government interference, even in the absence of public outcry or legislative intent.\n\n- Some fear that expansive interpretations of substantive due process may impede social progress, as laws that reflect evolving societal values and norms might be struck down due to outdated constitutional interpretations.\n\n- Lastly, the expansive use of substantive due process can be perceived as an overemphasis on individual rights at the expense of governmental interests, possibly leading to a reluctance to enact legislation aimed at public welfare.\n\nBy examining these points, your students",
      "source": "target",
